	<paragraphs xml:id="separable-form-details">
		<title> What Does <q>Separable</q> Mean?  </title>
		<p>
			The notation <m>f(x) \cdot g(y)</m> can be intimidating at first. It compresses a lot of ideas into a small expression. But don’t worry—we’ll break it down.
		</p>

		<p>
			In the definition, <m>f(x)</m> is just a stand-in for any expression that only involves the variable <m>x</m>. For example, it might be:
			<me>
				13\sin(3x), \quad (x^2 + 1)^{\cos x}, \quad 3x - 2e^{4x}, \quad \frac{2^x}{1+x}, \quad 1, \quad \text{etc.}
			</me>
		</p>

		<p>
			Likewise, <m>g(y)</m> stands for any expression involving only <m>y</m> and constants:
			<me>
				\sin(y+\cos y), \quad 3y^2 + 1, \quad \frac{1}{y}, \quad 1, \quad \text{etc.}
			</me>
		</p>

		<p>
			So when we say <m>f(x) \cdot g(y)</m>, we just mean any product where one factor depends only on <m>x</m> and the other only on <m>y</m>. Here are a few made-up examples:
			<me>
				\ob{3(3x - 2e^x)}^{f(x)} \cdot \ob{(y^2-1.7)}^{g(y)}, \quad
				\os{f(x)}{\os{\downarrow}{\left(\frac{1}{x+1}\right)}} \os{g(y)}{\os{\downarrow}{\left(\frac{y}{3}+7\right)}}, \quad
				\os{f(x)}{\os{\downarrow}{(-1)}} \cdot \os{g(y)}{\os{\downarrow}{(\pi)}}, \quad \text{etc.}
			</me>
		</p>

	</paragraphs>
	
	<paragraphs label="recognizing-separable-forms">
		<title> Recognizing Separable Forms </title>
		<p>
			Since the separation of variables method can only be applied to differential equations in separable form, it is crucial to be able to recognize this structure.
		</p>

		<p>
			Examples of separable differential equations include:
			<me>
				\frac{dy}{dx} = {\ub{(x^2 + 1) \cdot (y - 6)}_{\large f(x)\ \cdot\ g(y)}}^3 , \qquad
				\frac{dy}{dx} = \ub{\sin(y) \cdot \cos(x)}_{\large g(y)\ \cdot\ f(x)}.
			</me>
			Non-separable equations include:
			<me>
				\frac{dy}{dx} = \ub{-6x + 2y}_{\large f(x)\ +\ g(y)}, \quad
				\frac{dy}{dx} = {\ub{(x^2 + y) \cdot (y - 6)}_{\large f(x ,\ y)\ \cdot\ g(y)}}^3, \quad
				\frac{dy}{dx} = \ub{\cos(x - y)}_{\large f(x\ -\ y)}.
			</me>
		</p>

		<task label="chkpt-identifying-separable-2"><title> <em>Select-the-Best-Answer</em> </title>

			<statement>
				<p>
					Which of the following differential equations is not separable?
				</p>
			</statement>

			<choices>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad\ds\frac{dy}{dx} = \sin(x)\cos(y)</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. This equation is separable because it can be expressed as a product of functions involving only <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad\ds\frac{dy}{dx} = e^x \cdot y^2</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. This equation is separable as the variables are already separated by multiplication.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad\ds\frac{dy}{dx} = x + y</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct! This equation is not separable because the terms involving <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are added together, not multiplied.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\quad\ds\frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{x}{y}</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. This equation is separable because the variables are divided, which can still be separated into a product of functions.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
			
		</task>
	</paragraphs>

	<paragraphs label="special-separable-form">
		<title> A Special Separable Form </title>
		<p>
			As a special case, a differential equation can still be separable even if one or both variables do not explicitly appear. For example, the equations
			<me>
				\frac{dy}{dx} = 6x + 5, \qquad
				\frac{dy}{dx} = (y^2 + 7)^3, \qquad
				\frac{dy}{dx} = 15
			</me>,
			are all separable since they can be written as
			<me>
				\frac{dy}{dx} = (\underset{f(x)}{\underset{\uparrow}{ \vphantom{|} 6x }}) \cdot
				(\underset{g(y)}{\underset{\uparrow}{ \vphantom{|} 1 }})
				\qquad
				\frac{dy}{dx} = (\underset{f(x)}{\underset{\uparrow}{ \vphantom{|} 1 }}) \cdot
				\underset{g(y)}{\underset{\uparrow}{ \vphantom{|} (y^2 + 7)^3 }}
				\quad
				\frac{dy}{dx} = (\underset{f(x)}{\underset{\uparrow}{ \vphantom{|} 3 }}) \cdot
				(\underset{g(y)}{\underset{\uparrow}{ \vphantom{|} 5 }})
			</me>.
		</p>

		<p>
			While all three of these are in separable form and can be solved with the separation of variables method, the first and third equations are better suited for direct integration. 
		</p>

		<task label="chkpt-identifying-separable-3"><title> <em>True-or-False</em> </title>
			<statement correct="yes">
				<p>
					The differential equation,
					<me>
						\frac{dz}{dt} = \cos^2 z
					</me>,
					is separable
				</p>
			</statement>
			<feedback>
				<p>
					We can show it is separable by rewriting it as
					<me>
					\frac{dz}{dt} = \underset{f(t)}{\underbrace{(\ \pi + 5 \ )}} \cdot \underset{g(t)}{\underbrace{(\ 1 \ )}} \qquad \text{ or } \qquad \frac{dP}{dt} = \underset{f(z)}{\underbrace{(\ \cos^2 z \ )}} \cdot \underset{g(t)}{\underbrace{(\ \pi + 5 \ )}}
					</me>
				</p>
			</feedback>
		</task>
	</paragraphs>

