						<response>
							<p>
								<m>\quad\ds w' = e^Q e^{x}</m>
							</p>
						</response>
					</match>
				</cardsort>

			</task>
		</p>

		<p>
			As important as it is to show an equation is separable, it is equally important to identify when it is not.
		</p>

		<example xml:id="example-show-separable-2"><title> Non-Separable Equations </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Show the differential equations are NOT separable.
					<me>
						y^2\frac{d^2y}{dx^2} = x, \qquad
						xy' + 3x = y.
					</me>
				</p>
			</statement>
			
			<solution>
				<p>
					The first equation is a bit of a trick question to remind you of the first-order requirement of a separable equation. Since this equation is second-order, <em>separability does not apply</em>.
				</p>

				<p>
					This equation is first-order, but it is not separable. To see this, we can rearrange the equation to isolate the derivative:
					<md>
						<mrow> xy' + 3x = y </mrow>
						<mrow> xy' = y - 3x </mrow>
						<mrow> y' = \frac{y - 3x}{x} </mrow>
					</md>.
					Since there is no common factor of <m>x</m> or <m>y</m> in the numerator, the variables cannot be separated and the equation is not separable.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</example>

	</paragraphs>

	<fact label="separable-des-cyu-2">
